	<td class="wide1 high1">
	<h1>Dia de los Muertos</h1> 
		<p>A Mexican celebration of the dead.</p>
		<h2>Honoring our relatives</h2>
		<img src="day_of_the_dead.jpg" height="200" width="200" alt="Halloween image" align="left" hspace="10"/>
		<p>Originating in Mexico, Dia de los Muertos - Day of the Dead - is a two day celebration that is observed throughout many Latin American countries. A festival that pulls from Catholic and Aztec traditions, Dia de los Muertos, is marked by skeletons and skulls (<i>calacas</i>).</p>
		<p>The Day of the Dead celebration is built on the premise that the gates of heaven are opened on October 31st and the spirits of deceased loved ones may come down to earth to enjoy the festivities laid out for them. This sets the joyful tone of Dia de los Muertos. The Day of the Dead is not a time to mourn deceased loved ones, but to celebrate them. </p>		
		<p>Elaborate altars are arranged in homes and decorated with food, candles, and flowers. It is believed that properly celebrated spirits will offer protection and good luck in the coming year, so families can spend up to two month's salary in preparing an adequate altar.</p>
		<h3>Further Reading</h3>
		<ul>
		<li><a href="http://www.mexicansugarskull.com/support/dodhistory.html" target="_blank">Day of the Dead History - mexicansugarskull.com</a></li>
